{"parse":{"title":"Technology Shabbat","pageid":57456779,"revid":846509024,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Technology Shabbat</b> or <b><a class=\"mw-selflink selflink\">Tech Shabbat</a></b> are terms for a rest or cessation from the use of all technology with screens, ie smartphones, computers, tablets and television. The term was first coined in 2010 by filmmaker and internet pioneer <a href=\"/wiki/Tiffany_Shlain\" title=\"Tiffany Shlain\">Tiffany Shlain</a> and husband <a href=\"/wiki/UC_Berkeley\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"UC Berkeley\">UC Berkeley</a> robotics professor <a href=\"/wiki/Ken_Goldberg\" title=\"Ken Goldberg\">Ken Goldberg</a>. Shlain introduced the concept in a series of articles and films such as the <a href=\"/wiki/Harvard_Business_Review\" title=\"Harvard Business Review\">Harvard Business Review</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-Harvard_Business_Review_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Harvard_Business_Review-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> after participating in The National Day of Unplugging, which began in 2008 by Reboot, a nonprofit think tank of Jewish professionals, based in New York, Los Angeles and San Francisco.<sup id=\"cite_ref-NY_Times_2_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NY_Times_2-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The Technology Shabbat was inspired by the traditional Shabbat or Sabbath, a weekly day of rest in most popular religions.<sup id=\"cite_ref-CBS_News_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CBS_News-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-San_Francisco_Chronicle_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-San_Francisco_Chronicle-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> \n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Rituals\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Rituals</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Filmography\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Filmography</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Technology_Shabbat&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Although not named as such, the concept of a Technology Shabbat evolved as early on as the creation of the internet, with more people participating since the advent of portable devices, according to Mark Glaser, editor of MediaShift on <a href=\"/wiki/PBS\" title=\"PBS\">PBS</a>.org.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Oregonian_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Oregonian-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-MediaShift_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MediaShift-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> In the mid-1980s, <a href=\"/wiki/Secretary_of_State\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Secretary of State\">Secretary of State</a> <a href=\"/wiki/George_Shultz\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"George Shultz\">George Shultz</a> would take an hour each week in his office for quiet reflection with only a paper and pen.<sup id=\"cite_ref-NY_Times_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NY_Times-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> Shlain first disconnected in 2008, when her father, <a href=\"/wiki/Leonard_Shlain\" title=\"Leonard Shlain\">Leonard Shlain</a> was diagnosed with brain cancer. During his infrequent lucid moments, she'd turn off her cell phone.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Times_of_Israel_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Times_of_Israel-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Forward_9-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Forward-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> Soon after, she and her husband <a href=\"/wiki/Ken_Goldberg\" title=\"Ken Goldberg\">Ken Goldberg</a>, as members of Reboots, participated in the first annual National Day of Unplugging, and contributed a poem to commemorate the day, which was turned into a film by Shlain called \"Yelp: With Apologies to Allen Ginsberg's 'Howl'\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Oregonian_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Oregonian-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> Around that time, their family began the ritual of Technology Shabbats. \n</p><p><br />\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Rituals\">Rituals</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Technology_Shabbat&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Rituals\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>For a Technology Shabbat, all screens are turned off for 24 hours, and many of those who partake chose Friday night until Saturday night. Suggested alternatives to technology include activities like reading books, taking walks, visiting new neighborhoods, engaging in outdoor activities and using pen and paper.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Oregonian_5-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Oregonian-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>\u201cThe Internet is a vortex,\u201d  Portland writer Tammy Strobel told the <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Oregonian\" title=\"The Oregonian\">Oregonian</a></i> as the reason she and her husband turn off the computer on Sundays to observe Tech Sabbath. \u201cI can get lost in it for hours. And time is something we can never get back.\u201d<sup id=\"cite_ref-Oregonian_5-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Oregonian-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Among the rabbis who advocate unplugging for the Jewish Sabbath from Friday sunset to Saturday sunset are New York City's Elliot J. Cosgrove of Park Avenue Synagogue.<sup id=\"cite_ref-NY_Times_2_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NY_Times_2-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Filmography\">Filmography</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Technology_Shabbat&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Filmography\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The concept of Technology Shabbat has been featured in several films made by Shlain. These include \"<a href=\"/wiki/Connected:_An_Autoblogography_About_Love,_Death,_%26_Technology\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Connected: An Autoblogography About Love, Death, &amp; Technology\">Connected: An Autoblogography About Love, Death, &amp; Technology</a>\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-Jewish_News_of_N._California_10-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Jewish_News_of_N._California-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> in 2011, \"Yelp: With Apologies to Allen Ginsberg's 'Howl'\" in 2011, \n\"Technology Shabbats\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-Forward_9-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Forward-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> in 2013, \"A Case For Dreaming\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-Tech.co_11-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Tech.co-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> in 2014, and \n\"Making of a Mensch\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-Times_of_Israel_8-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Times_of_Israel-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> in 2015.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Technology_Shabbat&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 25em; -webkit-column-width: 25em; column-width: 25em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Harvard_Business_Review-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Harvard_Business_Review_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Shlain, Tiffany (March 1, 2013). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://hbr.org/2013/03/techs-best-feature-the-off-swi\">\"Tech's Best Feature: The Off Switch\"</a>. <i>Harvard Business Review</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">17 May</span> 2018</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Harvard+Business+Review&amp;rft.atitle=Tech%E2%80%99s+Best+Feature%3A+The+Off+Switch&amp;rft.date=2013-03-01&amp;rft.aulast=Shlain&amp;rft.aufirst=Tiffany&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fhbr.org%2F2013%2F03%2Ftechs-best-feature-the-off-swi&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATechnology+Shabbat\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-NY_Times_2-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-NY_Times_2_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-NY_Times_2_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Considine, Austin (March 17, 2010). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/18/fashion/18sabbath.html\">\"And on the Sabbath, the iPhones Shall Rest\"</a>. <i>NY Times 2</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">9 February</span> 2018</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=NY+Times+2&amp;rft.atitle=And+on+the+Sabbath%2C+the+iPhones+Shall+Rest&amp;rft.date=2010-03-17&amp;rft.aulast=Considine&amp;rft.aufirst=Austin&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2010%2F03%2F18%2Ffashion%2F18sabbath.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATechnology+Shabbat\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-CBS_News-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-CBS_News_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Ngak, Chenda (December 4, 2013). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.cbsnews.com/news/in-digital-age-where-do-parents-set-boundaries/\">\"In digital age, where do parents set boundaries?\"</a>. <i>CBS News</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">7 February</span> 2018</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=CBS+News&amp;rft.atitle=In+digital+age%2C+where+do+parents+set+boundaries%3F&amp;rft.date=2013-12-04&amp;rft.aulast=Ngak&amp;rft.aufirst=Chenda&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cbsnews.com%2Fnews%2Fin-digital-age-where-do-parents-set-boundaries%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATechnology+Shabbat\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-San_Francisco_Chronicle-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-San_Francisco_Chronicle_4-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.sfgate.com/homeandgarden/article/A-tour-of-an-unplugged-SF-home-4199145.php\">\"A tour of an unplugged SF home\"</a>. <i>San Francisco Chronicle</i